27 /******************************************************************************
28  HCI The variable argumnet lists of several HCI commands are split into
29  a header with pointers to pmalloc'd space. This define defines the size of
30  this pmalloc space. This allows the variable argument commands to be
31  resized according to memory constraints on the host controller.
32  If on XAP this in words.
33 
34  *****************************************************************************/
35 #define HCI_VAR_ARG_POOL_SIZE 32

1229 /******************************************************************************
1230  Packet boundary flag defines, these are already 'bit shifted'
1231  These are for use with ACL only, for SCO use 00 (reserved)
1232  The pbf is 2 bits, a start flag can be 00 or 10 ie bit 0 = 0 , the
1233  continuation flag is bit 0 = 1. So when testing for a start flag, can use the
1234  the logic that if it is not a continuation flag it must be a start one.
1235  *****************************************************************************/
1236 #define HCI_PKT_BOUNDARY_FLAG_START_NONFLUSH ((hci_packet_boundary_flag_t)0)
1237 #define HCI_PKT_BOUNDARY_FLAG_CONT ((hci_packet_boundary_flag_t)0x1000)
1238 #define HCI_PKT_BOUNDARY_FLAG_START_FLUSH ((hci_packet_boundary_flag_t)0x2000)
1239 #define HCI_PKT_BOUNDARY_MASK ((hci_packet_boundary_flag_t)0x3000)

1418 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
1419  *
1420  * HCI event mask values
1421  * As 8 byte quantity split into two uint32_t so require high and low
1422  * part masks.
1423  * NB: as currently assigned, these are a simple function of the
1424  * corresponding HCI event code (HCI_EV_*).
1425  *
1426  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
1427 
1428 /*
1429  * Some compilers complain about shifts by out of range values (negative or
1430  * more than 32) even if they're on dead code paths. Strictly, this complaint
1431  * is not necessary as even though such a shift produces undefined behaviour,
1432  * the ANSI C spec explicitly states that this is not a problem on code paths
1433  * that aren't taken because of a constant expression in a short-circuit
1434  * operator. See section 6.4 and particularly footnote 55.
1435  *
1436  * However, it's better if header files don't emit warnings so to keep such
1437  * compilers happy we add a second test. At the end of the day, the expression
1438  * value is still constant so it doesn't cost us anything. Since the same test
1439  * is used in more than one place, it's placed in a macro to avoid repetition.
1440  */
1441 
1442 #define HCI_EV_MASK_SHIFT_IS_SAFE(amount) ((amount) >= 0 && (amount) < 32)
1443 
1444 #define HCI_EV_MASK_SAFE_SINGLE_BIT_MASK(amount) \
1445  ((hci_event_mask_t) \
1446  (HCI_EV_MASK_SHIFT_IS_SAFE(amount) ? \
1447  1UL << (HCI_EV_MASK_SHIFT_IS_SAFE(amount) ? (amount) : 0) : \
1448  0))
1449 
1450 /* Note, event 1 ends up in bit 0, hence the extra -1 in HCI_EV_MASK_HI and
1451  HCI_EV_MASK_LO */
1452 
1453 #define HCI_EV_MASK_HI(x) HCI_EV_MASK_SAFE_SINGLE_BIT_MASK((int) (x) - 33)
1454 #define HCI_EV_MASK_LO(x) HCI_EV_MASK_SAFE_SINGLE_BIT_MASK((int) (x) - 1)
1455 
1456 /* For page 2 event mask, event 64 ends up in bit 0, hence -64 for
1457  HCI_EV_MASK_LO2 and -96 for HCI_EV_MASK_HI2 */
1458 
1459 #define HCI_EV_MASK_HI2(x) HCI_EV_MASK_SAFE_SINGLE_BIT_MASK((int) (x) - 96)
1460 #define HCI_EV_MASK_LO2(x) HCI_EV_MASK_SAFE_SINGLE_BIT_MASK((int) (x) - 64)

1614 /* Any event introduced after Synchronous Connection Changed Event is by
1615  default masked so old hosts working with new controllers don't receive
1616  events they don't enderstand */

2224 /*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*
2225  *
2226  * Coding of BR/EDR Features. Features is 64 bits long, it is sent across HCI
2227  * as an array of 8 uint8s, hence the feature definitions are split into 8 bit
2228  * quantities. The HCI_FEATURE_MASK/INDEX and HCI_FEATURE_IS_SUPPORTED
2229  * macros should be used to manipulate individual bits. Note that this last
2230  * macro returns non-zero (not necessarily 1) for a supported feature.
2231  *
2232  * If a feature is present the bit is set.
2233  *
2234  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
2235 #define LMP_FEATURES_THREE_SLOT_PACKETS_BIT 0
2236 #define LMP_FEATURES_FIVE_SLOT_PACKETS_BIT 1
2237 #define LMP_FEATURES_ENCRYPTION_BIT 2
2238 #define LMP_FEATURES_SLOT_OFFSET_BIT 3
2239 #define LMP_FEATURES_TIMING_ACCURACY_BIT 4
2240 #define LMP_FEATURES_SWITCH_BIT 5
2241 #define LMP_FEATURES_HOLD_MODE_BIT 6
2242 #define LMP_FEATURES_SNIFF_MODE_BIT 7
2243 /* Bit 8 was Park Mode */
2244 #define LMP_FEATURES_RSSI_BIT 9
2245 #define LMP_FEATURES_CHANNEL_QUALITY_DRIVEN_DATA_RATE_BIT 10
2246 #define LMP_FEATURES_SCO_LINK_BIT 11
2247 #define LMP_FEATURES_HV2_PACKETS_BIT 12
2248 #define LMP_FEATURES_HV3_PACKETS_BIT 13
2249 #define LMP_FEATURES_U_LAW_BIT 14
2250 #define LMP_FEATURES_A_LAW_BIT 15
2251 #define LMP_FEATURES_CVSD_BIT 16
2252 #define LMP_FEATURES_PAGING_SCHEME_BIT 17
2253 #define LMP_FEATURES_POWER_CONTROL_BIT 18
2254 #define LMP_FEATURES_TRANSPARENT_SCO_BIT 19
2255 #define LMP_FEATURES_FLOW_CONTROL_LAG_BIT0_BIT 20
2256 #define LMP_FEATURES_FLOW_CONTROL_LAG_BIT1_BIT 21
2257 #define LMP_FEATURES_FLOW_CONTROL_LAG_BIT2_BIT 22
2258 #define LMP_FEATURES_BCAST_ENCRYPTION_BIT 23
2259 /* Bit 24 was Scatter Mode */
2260 #define LMP_FEATURES_MR_2MBPS_BIT 25
2261 #define LMP_FEATURES_MR_3MBPS_BIT 26
2262 #define LMP_FEATURES_ENHANCED_INQUIRY_SCAN_BIT 27
2263 #define LMP_FEATURES_INTERLACED_INQUIRY_SCAN_BIT 28
2264 #define LMP_FEATURES_INTERLACED_PAGE_SCAN_BIT 29

2268 #define LMP_FEATURES_EV5_PACKETS_BIT 33
2269 #define LMP_FEATURES_ABSENCE_MASKS_BIT 34
2270 #define LMP_FEATURES_AFH_CAPABLE_SLAVE_BIT 35
2271 #define LMP_FEATURES_AFH_CLASSIFICATION_SLAVE_BIT 36
2272 #define LMP_FEATURES_BR_EDR_NOT_SUPPORTED_BIT 37
2273 #define LMP_FEATURES_LE_SUPPORTED_CONTROLLER_BIT 38
2274 #define LMP_FEATURES_3SLOT_MR_BIT 39
2275 #define LMP_FEATURES_5SLOT_MR_BIT 40
2276 #define LMP_FEATURES_SNIFF_SUB_RATE_BIT 41
2277 #define LMP_FEATURES_ENCRYPTION_PAUSE_RESUME_BIT 42
2278 #define LMP_FEATURES_AFH_CAPABLE_MASTER_BIT 43
2279 #define LMP_FEATURES_AFH_CLASSIFICATION_MASTER_BIT 44
2280 #define LMP_FEATURES_MR_ESCO_2MBPS_BIT 45
2281 #define LMP_FEATURES_MR_ESCO_3MBPS_BIT 46
2282 #define LMP_FEATURES_3SLOT_ESCO_MR_BIT 47
2283 #define LMP_FEATURES_EXTENDED_INQUIRY_RESPONSE_BIT 48
2284 #define LMP_FEATURES_SIMULTANEOUS_LE_BR_EDR_CAPABLE_CONTROLLER_BIT 49
2285 /* Bits 49-50 were Alphanumeric Pin Aware/Capable */
2286 #define LMP_FEATURES_SIMPLE_PAIRING_BIT 51
2287 #define LMP_FEATURES_ENCAPSULATED_PDU_BIT 52
2288 /* Bit 53 Erroneous Data Reporting (not supported) */
2289 #define LMP_FEATURES_NON_FLUSHABLE_PBF_BIT 54
2290 /* Bit 55 reserved */
2291 #define LMP_FEATURES_LINK_SUPERVISION_TIMEOUT_BIT 56

2293 #define LMP_FEATURES_ENHANCED_POWER_CONTROL_BIT 58
2294 /* Bit 59 was (briefly) BR/EDR Secure Connections */
2295 
2296 /* Bits 59-62 reserved */
2297 #define LMP_FEATURES_EXTENDED_FEATURES_BIT 63

2299 #define HCI_FEATURE_MASK(bit) (1U << ((bit) & 7))
2300 #define HCI_FEATURE_INDEX(bit) ((bit) / 8)
2301 #define HCI_FEATURE_IS_SUPPORTED(bit, array) \
2302  ((array)[HCI_FEATURE_INDEX(bit)] & HCI_FEATURE_MASK(bit))

2507 /*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*
2508  *
2509  * Coding of ULP Features. Features is 64 bits long, it is sent across HCI as
2510  * an array of 8 uint8s, hence the feature definitions are split into 8 bit
2511  * quantities. The ULP_FEATURE_MASK/INDEX and ULP_FEATURE_IS_SUPPORTED
2512  * macros should be used to manipulate individual bits. Note that this last
2513  * macro returns non-zero (not necessarily 1) for a supported feature.
2514  *
2515  * If a feature is present the bit is set.
2516  *
2517  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
2518 #define ULP_FEATURE_ENCRYPTION 0
2519 #define ULP_FEATURE_CONNECTION_PARAMETERS_REQUEST_PROCEDURE 1
2520 #define ULP_FEATURE_EXTENDED_REJECT_INDICATION 2
2521 #define ULP_FEATURE_SLAVE_INITIATED_FEATURES_EXCHANGE 3
2522 #define ULP_FEATURE_LE_PING 4
2523 #define ULP_FEATURE_DATA_LENGTH_EXTENSION 5
2524 #define ULP_FEATURE_LL_PRIVACY 6
2525 #define ULP_FEATURE_2LE_PHY 8
2526 #define ULP_FEATURE_STABLE_MODULATION_INDEX 9
2527 #define ULP_FEATURE_CHANNEL_SELECTION_ALGORITHM_2 14
2528 
2529 /* Note that this is still to be defined. i.e. FIPD has T.B.D.
2530  * Use 10 for now
2531  */
2532 #define ULP_FEATURE_BLR_PHY 10
2533 
2534 #define ULP_FEATURE_MASK(feature) (1U << ((feature) & 15))
2535 #define ULP_FEATURE_INDEX(feature) ((feature)/16)
2536 
2537 /* Query macro */
2538 #define ULP_FEATURE_IS_SUPPORTED(featureset, feature) \
2539  ( (featureset)[ULP_FEATURE_INDEX(feature)] \
2540  & ULP_FEATURE_MASK(feature))

2837 /*-----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
2838  *
2839  * Variable Argument HCI definitions, used to auto-size the HCI
2840  *
2841  * To restrict the maximum pool size required the variable length HCI commands
2842  * (Payload of up to 255 bytes (Not 256)), the HCI payload is split into several
2843  * chunks of size HCI_VAR_ARG_POOL_SIZE. The HCI command structure, points to
2844  * a number of these blocks. Each of these blocks are pmalloc'd on demand and
2845  * the number allocated depends on the number of arguments required at that
2846  * point in time. Each of these blocks holds a number of packets per ptr
2847  * depending on the packet size.
2848  *
2849  * The calculations below, auto-size the number of pmalloc'd pointer blocks
2850  * required and the number of packets that each of the blocks can hold.
2851  *
2852  * HCI_ARC_CONVERT(input_struct) - This makes the size of the structure the
2853  * same number on windows and XAP. Hence
2854  * allowing xap friendly code.
2855  *
2856  * HCI_PMALLOC_ARC_CONVERT - This takes into account that
2857  * HCI_VAR_ARG_POOL_SIZE is in XAP words.
2858  *
2859  * So for example, the handle complete calculations come out as follows:
2860  *
2861  * 254 = Max Payload size - HCI_byte_sizeof(num_handles)
2862  * HCI_VAR_ARG_POOL_SIZE=32 :Fixed size of POOL.
2863  * HCI_BYTE_SIZE_OF_HANDLE_COMPLETE_T=4 :Number of bytes sent across the
2864  * HCI interface for each handle_complete.
2865  * HCI_ARC_CONVERT(HANDLE_COMPLETE_T)=2
2866  *
2867  * HCI_EV_HANDLE_COMPLETES_PER_PTR =(32/2)=16
2868  * HCI_EV_NUM_HANDLE_COMPLETE_PACKET_PTRS =((254/4)+16-1) / 16 = 4
2869  *
2870  * The (16-1) which os seen in HCI_EV_NUM_HANDLE_COMPLETE_PACKET_PTRS, is
2871  * used to accomodate the rounding down error, caused by integer division.
2872  * If an extra block is required, this calculation will ensure it is
2873  * allocated.
2874  *
2875  *------------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
2876 #define HCI_ARC_CONVERT(input_struct) (sizeof(input_struct)*sizeof(uint8_t)/sizeof(uint16_t))
2877 #define HCI_PMALLOC_ARC_CONVERT zpmalloc(HCI_VAR_ARG_POOL_SIZE * sizeof(uint16_t))
2878 
2879 #define HCI_NAME_LENGTH 248
2880 #define HCI_LOCAL_NAME_BYTES_PER_PTR HCI_VAR_ARG_POOL_SIZE
2881 #define HCI_LOCAL_NAME_BYTE_PACKET_PTRS ((HCI_NAME_LENGTH + HCI_LOCAL_NAME_BYTES_PER_PTR -1) / HCI_LOCAL_NAME_BYTES_PER_PTR)
2882 
2883 #define HCI_BYTE_SIZE_OF_HANDLE_COMPLETE_T 4
2884 #define HCI_EV_HANDLE_COMPLETES_PER_PTR (HCI_VAR_ARG_POOL_SIZE/HCI_ARC_CONVERT(HANDLE_COMPLETE_T))
2885 #define HCI_EV_NUM_HANDLE_COMPLETE_PACKET_PTRS ( ((254 / HCI_BYTE_SIZE_OF_HANDLE_COMPLETE_T) + HCI_EV_HANDLE_COMPLETES_PER_PTR -1) / HCI_EV_HANDLE_COMPLETES_PER_PTR)
2886 
2887 #define HCI_HOST_NUM_COMPLETED_PACKETS_PER_PTR HCI_EV_HANDLE_COMPLETES_PER_PTR
2888 #define HCI_HOST_NUM_COMPLETED_PACKET_PTRS HCI_EV_NUM_HANDLE_COMPLETE_PACKET_PTRS
2889 
2890 /* HCI_ARC_CONVERT(HCI_INQ_RESULT_T) is not used for the following definition
2891  because it is only guaranteed to be correct on the XAP and the definition
2892  here is also used by BCHS on various other architectures. Crucially, BCHS
2893  needs to be able to get the correct value of HCI_MAX_INQ_RESULT_PTRS as
2894  otherwise they have no way of determining the size of various DM event
2895  primitives that return inquiry results. Unlike HCI, Bluestack uses the
2896  Bluecore Friendly Format for physical interfaces and this specifies that
2897  pointers are passed as 16 bit zeros, the data (to which these pointed)
2898  follows at the end of the primitive. Therefore BCHS needs to know how
2899  many of these pointers have been sent. So we define a static value here
2900  and then use a compile time assert in nonhci_convert.c to ensure that
2901  this equals HCI_ARC_CONVERT(HCI_INQ_RESULT_T) when compiling on the xap.
2902  See B-30015. */
2903 #ifdef __KALIMBA32__
2904 #define KAL32_SIZE_OF_HCI_INQ_RESULT_T 10
2905 #define HCI_MAX_INQ_RESULT_PER_PTR (HCI_VAR_ARG_POOL_SIZE/KAL32_SIZE_OF_HCI_INQ_RESULT_T)
2906 #else
2907 #define XAP_SIZE_OF_HCI_INQ_RESULT_T 10
2908 #define HCI_MAX_INQ_RESULT_PER_PTR (HCI_VAR_ARG_POOL_SIZE/XAP_SIZE_OF_HCI_INQ_RESULT_T)
2909 #endif
2910 #define HCI_BYTE_SIZE_OF_HCI_INQ_RESULT_T 14
2911 #define HCI_MAX_INQ_RESULT_PTRS ( ((254 / HCI_BYTE_SIZE_OF_HCI_INQ_RESULT_T) + HCI_MAX_INQ_RESULT_PER_PTR -1) / HCI_MAX_INQ_RESULT_PER_PTR)
2912 
2913 #define HCI_BYTE_SIZE_OF_HCI_IAC_LAP 3
2914 #define HCI_IAC_LAP_PER_PTR (HCI_VAR_ARG_POOL_SIZE/HCI_ARC_CONVERT(uint24_t))
2915 #define HCI_IAC_LAP_PTRS ( ((254 / HCI_BYTE_SIZE_OF_HCI_IAC_LAP) + HCI_IAC_LAP_PER_PTR -1) / HCI_IAC_LAP_PER_PTR)
2916 
2917 #define HCI_EVENT_PKT_LENGTH 255
2918 #define HCI_LOOPBACK_BYTES_PER_PTR HCI_VAR_ARG_POOL_SIZE
2919 #define HCI_LOOPBACK_BYTE_PACKET_PTRS ((HCI_EVENT_PKT_LENGTH + HCI_LOOPBACK_BYTES_PER_PTR -1) / HCI_LOOPBACK_BYTES_PER_PTR)

2965 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
2966  * PURPOSE
2967  * If the DM is on-chip we combine the DM and HCI structures to save code
2968  * space at the sacrifice of a few words of pmalloc space.
2969  *
2970  * CAUTION
2971  * Whenever we add a new structure, we need to moidfy
2972  * hci_convert/layout.pl so that the modified primitives can be
2973  * serialized appropriately.
2974  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
2975 #ifdef DONT_BREAK_HCI_H
2976 #define ADDED_BD_ADDRESS
2977 #define ADDED_TYPED_BD_ADDRESS
2978 #define ADDED_BD_ADDR_TRANSPORT
2979 #else
2980 #define ADDED_BD_ADDRESS BD_ADDR_T bd_addr;
2981 #define ADDED_TYPED_BD_ADDRESS TYPED_BD_ADDR_T addrt;
2982 #define ADDED_BD_ADDR_TRANSPORT TP_BD_ADDR_T tp_addrt;
2983 #endif

4891 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
4892  * PURPOSE
4893  * Host Number of Completed Packets command
4894  *
4895  * NOTE: Variable struct. num_handles denotes how many connection
4896  * handles follow and then the same number of counts.
4897  *
4898  * Max Size of HCI payload = 255, Variable Size = 255-(uint8_t) = 254
4899  *
4900  * HCI_BYTE_SIZE_OF_HANDLE_COMPLETE_T - Byte size of HANDLE_COMPLETE_T
4901  * when transmitted across the HCI interface.
4902  * HCI_HOST_NUM_COMPLETED_PACKETS_PER_PTR - Number of HANDLE_COMPLETE_T's
4903  * in a pointed at block.
4904  * HCI_HOST_NUM_COMPLETED_PACKET_PTRS - Number of pointer blocks.
4905  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
4906 
4907 typedef struct
4908 {
4909  HCI_COMMAND_COMMON_T common;
4910  uint8_t num_handles;
4911 
4912  /*
4913  * HANDLE_COMPLETE_T (*num_completed_pkts_ptr[4])[16]
4914  *
4915  * The pointers below, point to
4916  * HANDLE_COMPLETE_T[HCI_HOST_NUM_COMPLETED_PACKETS_PER_PTR],
4917  * ie a pointer to the beginning of 16 HANDLE_COMPLETE_T.
4918  */
4919  HANDLE_COMPLETE_T *num_completed_pkts_ptr[HCI_HOST_NUM_COMPLETED_PACKET_PTRS];
4920 
4921 } HCI_HOST_NUM_COMPLETED_PACKETS_T;
4922

5807 
5808 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
5809  * PURPOSE
5810  * Read Local Supported Codecs command
5811  *
5812  * NOTE: Variable struct.
5813  * We have read num_of_supported_codecs and
5814  * num_of_supported_vendor_specific_codecs.
5815  *
5816  * MAX Size of HCI payload = 255, Variable Size = 255-2*(uint8_t) = 253
5817  * which need to be splitted in half. We decided to use 128 octets( = 64
5818  * XAP words = 128 codecs of 1 octet each) for supported_codecs and 125
5819  * for vendor_specific_codecs. However, for the moment we will only use
5820  * 64 octets ( = 32 XAP words = 16 codecs of 4 octets each) for the
5821  * vendor_specific_codecs.
5822  *
5823  * HCI_SUPPORTED_CODECS_PER_PTR - Number of XAP uint8_t`s in a block.
5824  * On a XAP sizeof(uint8_t) = sizeof(uint16_t) = 1 (XAP word i.e. 2 octets).
5825  * The firmware will put a uint8_t in each XAP uint8_t; therefore the upper
5826  * bits of a XAP uint_8 will be empty.
5827  * HCI_SUPPORTED_CODECS_PTRS - Number of pointers to blocks.
5828  *
5829  * HCI_VENDOR_SPECIFIC_CODECS_PER_PTR - Number of uint32_t's in a block
5830  * HCI_VENDOR_SPECIFIC_CODECS_PTRS - Number of pointers to blocks.
5831  *---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
5832 typedef struct
5833 {
5834  HCI_COMMAND_COMMON_T common;
5835 } HCI_READ_LOCAL_SUPP_CODECS_T;
5836 
5837 typedef struct
5838 {
5839  uint8_t num_of_supported_codecs;
5840  uint8_t *supported_codecs[HCI_SUPPORTED_CODECS_PTRS];
5841 
5842  uint8_t num_of_supported_vendor_specific_codecs;
5843  uint32_t *vendor_specific_codecs[HCI_VENDOR_SPECIFIC_CODECS_PTRS];
5844 
5845 } HCI_READ_LOCAL_SUPP_CODECS_RET_T;
5846 
5847

6852 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
6853  * PURPOSE
6854  * Allow manufacturer's extension commands to go over HCI. These are
6855  * used for:
6856  *
6857  * 1. To tunnel additional protocols over HCI (see specification
6858  * bc01-s-023c). These are carried in BlueCore-Friendly format.
6859  * 2. For debug commands.
6860  *
6861  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
6862 typedef union
6863 {
6864  uint8_t *bcf; /* carries tunnelled primitives */
6865  HCI_DEBUG_REQUEST_T debug_request; /* carries debug requests */
6866 } MNFR_EXTN_PAYLOAD_T;
6867 
6868 
6869 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
6870  * PURPOSE
6871  * Allow manufacturer's extension commands to go over HCI. These are
6872  * used for:
6873  *
6874  * 1. To tunnel additional protocols over HCI (see specification
6875  * bc01-s-023c).
6876  * 2. For debug commands.
6877  *
6878  * The payload_descriptor indicates the channel ID and contains two
6879  * bits which control fragmentation and reassembly of HCI commands
6880  * into protocol primitives. Bits in the payload descriptor are:
6881  *
6882  * 7 Indicates 'fragment end'
6883  * 6 Indicates 'fragment start'
6884  * [5:0] Channel ID
6885  *
6886  * Channel IDs in the range 0 to 15 are equivalent to the BCSP protocol
6887  * IDs, although some are not used. Channel ID CHANNEL_ID_DEBUG indicates
6888  * that the command is a debug command.
6889  *
6890  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
6891 
6892 #define FRAGMENT_END (0x80)
6893 #define FRAGMENT_START (0x40)
6894 #define CHANNEL_ID_DEBUG (20) /* same as HOSTIO_PROTOCOL_DEBUG used in fw*/
6895 #define CHANNEL_ID_MASK (0x3F)
6896 
6897 typedef struct
6898 {
6899  HCI_COMMAND_COMMON_T common;
6900  uint8_t payload_descriptor;
6901  MNFR_EXTN_PAYLOAD_T payload;
6902 } HCI_MNFR_EXTENSION_T;
6903 
6904 typedef struct
6905 {
6906  HCI_COMMAND_COMMON_T common;
6907  uint8_t *vs_data_part[HCI_VS_DATA_BYTE_PACKET_PTRS];
6908 } HCI_VS_COMMAND_T;
6909 
6910 typedef struct
6911 {
6912  uint8_t *vs_data_part[HCI_VS_DATA_BYTE_PACKET_PTRS];
6913 } HCI_VS_COMMAND_RET_T;
6914

6958 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
6959  * PURPOSE
6960  * Allow manufacturer's extension events to go over HCI or to Bluestack.
6961  * These are used for:
6962  *
6963  * 1. To tunnel additional protocols over HCI (see specification
6964  * bc01-s-023c). These are carried in BlueCore-Friendly format.
6965  * 2. For responses to debug commands over HCI.
6966  * 3. Vendor specific events to go to Bluestack (If DM is on chip).
6967  *
6968  * Note: If new vendor specific event is added in EV_MNFR_EXTN_PAYLOAD_T
6969  * then HCI_EV_MNFR_EXTENSION_PARAM_LEN length need to be revised.
6970  *
6971  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
6972 typedef union
6973 {
6974  uint8_t *bcf; /* carries tunnelled primitives */
6975  uint8_t vendor_event; /* carries vendor event code */
6976  HCI_EV_DEBUG_T debug_event; /* carries debug events */
6977  HCI_EV_CSB_AFH_MAP_AVAILABLE_T csb_afh_map_available; /*carries afh data */
6978  /* Add new vendor specific event here */
6979 } EV_MNFR_EXTN_PAYLOAD_T;
6980 
6981 
6982 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
6983  * PURPOSE
6984  * Allow manufacturer's extension eventes to go over HCI. These are
6985  * used for:
6986  *
6987  * 1. To tunnel additional protocols over HCI (see specification
6988  * bc01-s-023c).
6989  * 2. For responses to debug commands.
6990  *
6991  * The payload_descriptor indicates the channel ID and contains two
6992  * bits which control fragmentation and reassembly of HCI commands
6993  * into protocol primitives. Bits in the payload descriptor are:
6994  *
6995  * 7 Indicates 'fragment end'
6996  * 6 Indicates 'fragment start'
6997  * [5:0] Channel ID
6998  *
6999  * Channel IDs in the range 0 to 15 are equivalent to the BCSP protocol
7000  * IDs, although some are not used. Channel ID CHANNEL_ID_DEBUG indicates
7001  * that the command is a debug command.
7002  *
7003  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
7004 typedef struct
7005 {
7006  HCI_EVENT_COMMON_T event;
7007 /* coding of payload_descriptor is the same as HCI_MNFR_EXTENSION_T */
7008  uint8_t payload_descriptor;
7009  EV_MNFR_EXTN_PAYLOAD_T payload;
7010 
7011 } HCI_EV_MNFR_EXTENSION_T;

7038  *

7040  * in a pointed at block.
7041  * HCI_MAX_INQ_RESULT_PTRS - Number of pointer blocks.

7051  bt_clock_offset_t clock_offset;
7052 } HCI_INQ_RESULT_T;

7060  */

7062  * The array of pointers below, point to
7063  * HCI_INQ_RESULT_T[HCI_MAX_INQ_RESULT_PER_PTR],
7064  * ie a pointer to the beginning of X HCI_INQ_RESULT_T.
7065  */
7066  HCI_INQ_RESULT_T *result[HCI_MAX_INQ_RESULT_PTRS];
7067 
7068 } HCI_EV_INQUIRY_RESULT_T;

8078 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
8079  * PURPOSE
8080  * ULP Advertising
8081  * HCI ULP Advertising Report Event (0x3E, subevent code: 0x02)
8082  *
8083  * Note:
8084  * As per spec (Vol-2/Part-E/Section-7.7.65.2), "The Controller may queue these
8085  * advertising reports and send information from multiple devices in one LE Advertising
8086  * Report event.."
8087  * We because of memory constraints in on-chip variants, don't queue advertising
8088  * reports. So each advertising report corresponds to a single advertising indicator
8089  * from single peer device.
8090  *
8091  * Also data field is defined as an array of pointers because of the framework to handle
8092  * variable length parameters in HCI commands/events and to move such variable length
8093  * parameters into a separate memory block.
8094  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
8095 typedef struct
8096 {
8097  HCI_ULP_EVENT_COMMON_T event;
8098  uint8_t num_reports;
8099  uint8_t event_type;
8100  uint8_t address_type;
8101  BD_ADDR_T address;
8102  uint8_t length_data;
8103  uint8_t *data[HCI_ULP_ADVERTISING_DATA_PTRS];
8104  int8_t rssi;
8105 } HCI_EV_ULP_ADVERTISING_REPORT_T;
8106

8109  * ULP Connection Update
8110  * HCI ULP Connection Update Complete Event (0x3E, subevent code: 0x03)

8115  HCI_ULP_EVENT_COMMON_T event;

8119  uint16_t conn_latency;
8120  uint16_t supervision_timeout;
8121 } HCI_EV_ULP_CONNECTION_UPDATE_COMPLETE_T;

8166 } HCI_EV_ULP_REMOTE_CONNECTION_PARAMETER_REQUEST_T;
8167 
8168 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
8169  * PURPOSE
8170  * ULP Encryption
8171  * HCI ULP Read Local P-256 Public Key Complete Event (0x3E,
8172  * subevent code: 0x08)
8173  * NOTE
8174  * The local_p256_public_key parameter is in the spec as an array of
8175  * octets, however, it comes out of the ECC code as a little endian array
8176  * of words and we'll serialise that as a little endian array of octets,
8177  * making the octets on the wire correct. Making it a uint8_t would use
8178  * twice as much memory for this struct and require code to unpack the ECC
8179  * output into local_p256_public_key.
8180  *
8181  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
8182 typedef struct
8183 {
8184  HCI_ULP_EVENT_COMMON_T event;
8185  hci_return_t status;
8186  uint16_t local_p256_public_key[32];
8187 } HCI_EV_ULP_READ_LOCAL_P256_PUB_KEY_COMPLETE_T;
8188 
8189 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
8190  * PURPOSE
8191  * ULP Encryption
8192  * HCI ULP Generate DHKey Complete Event (0x3E, subevent code: 0x09)
8193  *
8194  * NOTE
8195  * The dhkey parameter is in the spec as an array of octets, however,
8196  * it comes out of the ECC code as a little endian array of words and
8197  * we'll serialise that as a little endian array of octets, making the
8198  * octets on the wire correct. Making it a uint8_t would use twice as much
8199  * memory for this struct and require code to unpack the ECC output into
8200  * dhkey.
8201  *
8202  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
8203 typedef struct
8204 {
8205  HCI_ULP_EVENT_COMMON_T event;
8206  hci_return_t status;
8207  uint16_t dhkey[16];
8208 } HCI_EV_ULP_GENERATE_DHKEY_COMPLETE_T;
8209 
8210 /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*

8223  uint16_t max_rx_time;
8224 } HCI_EV_ULP_DATA_LENGTH_CHANGE_T;
8225

8435  /*----------------------------------------------------------------------------*
8436  * PURPOSE
8437  * Command Complete Event
8438  * Use specific return structures for particular commands
8439  *
8440  * The status argument, should in all rights be in the argument_ptr
8441  * list but, as every command complete event returns a status we have
8442  * moved it into the body of the structure to prevent us having malloc
8443  * commands which only return a status.
8444  *----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
8445 typedef struct
8446 {
8447  HCI_EVENT_COMMON_T event;
8448  uint8_t num_hci_command_pkts;
8449  hci_op_code_t op_code; /* op code of command that caused this event */
8450  hci_return_t status;
8451  HCI_COMMAND_COMPLETE_ARGS_T* argument_ptr; /* Pointer to arguments */
8452 } HCI_EV_COMMAND_COMPLETE_T;
